Second optimization practice. Network exercise: Plan to invade China¶

DISCLAIMER! THE FOLLOWING THREE PARAGRAPHS ARE NOT USEFUL FOR GRADING PURPOSES, IF YOU ARE RUNNING OUT OF TIME OR DO NOT WANT TO READ THAT MUCH, YOU CAN SKIP IT

Geopolitical earthquakes are happening along Southeast Asia. The shadow of China along all the different countries located on Asia Pacific, the Indochinese Peninsula and all the diferent islands located on the Chinese sea is creating a polarized world in where war between US suporters and China suporters may arise somewhere along the near future; and that is the reason why the US army thought about the posibility of invading China and neutralizing some of its most important cities and control nodes. Since it would be a very important incursion and an inflexion point for the future, the US army was not very confident about the creation of this incursion, but analyzing the information from the chips and memory card of the chinese balloon shot down back on February 4th, 2023, some engineers were able to create a conexion to some of the Chinese army servers and were able to kow the amount of soldiers located in the army garrisons in each province, as well as some paths between some provinces which are too crowded with mines and defenses that it would be either impossible or an authentic slaughter for the US troops

And after knowing this information, the US finally created a plan to neutralize China, since the best defense is a good attack: the US army will take advantage of the civil war on Myanmar, which has a frontier shared with China, on the southern province of Yunnan, so that the troops can enter its territory without any kind of risk. They would also use a High Altitude Electromagnetic Pulse to make unusable all kinds of aircrafts and artillery, which would end up in fights between only chinese grounded soldiers

But, despite the fact that the contentious invasion will take place, the US would not like to annihilate China, just to infer fear onto its poblation. This means that the US would like to take control of the most strategic and mainly productive provinces causing the fewer casualties possible, which would imply the encountering of the fewest amount of soldiers possible in the enemy garrisons

We will try to simulate the invasion in this assignment, but since we do not have access to the information given to the US army about the garrisons personal in the Chinese provinces, we will have to create it from scratch (or better said, based on random inputs). For the initialization of the network we will need to take into account some things. Firstly, we will have to define the name of the provinces, defined in the list provinces, and then we need to know which province is connected to each other. This is performed throught the creation of a dictionary, borders, in where the provinces sharing a border with the one provided on the dictionary key are stored in a list.

Note: since the problem is stated in a maner in where it is not possible to return by the same path taken previously, we had to take into account those provinces with some problematic borders. For example, Beijing connects to Tianjin and Hebei, And Tianjin connects with Hebei and Beijing, which imply an internal cycle between those three provinces, and if any of these would be a mandatory province to conquer, it would not be possible to take a path to exit as we would encounter with the reinforcements in Hebei's garrison either way. That is the reason why we appended new paths on those territories, like the Beijing - Liaoning and the Tianjin - Shandong paths. The same is applied to Both Hong Kong and Macau, which both only border naturally with Guangdong

prohibited_paths = [["Yunnan", "Sichuan"], ["Chongqing", "Shaanxi"], ["Hunan", "Jiangxi"]]

And now, when all the necessary information is initialized, we can finally start with the model initialization

The first thing to take into account is the way we are going to approach the problem. The most straightforward manner is to first make use of the variables previously intiialized: the list provinces is made a set of the different provinces in where the garrisons are located (model.nodes), the list allborders is also a set of all the possible paths between these provinces, and the dictionary armies is initialized as a parameter, whose output is the amount of soldiers in the provided province

Now, the main variable to take look afterwards is the variable $x$. It is set to be a binary variable, and it is used to define a certain path to be a 0 or a 1, depending on if the path from province $o$ to province $d$ is being used in the final pathing (1) or not (0). Notice that, since the default value is being set to 0, all paths are defined as a zero even if there exist no path between them. Using the previous example, the path defined from Henan to Gansu is defined as a 0 as that path cannot be traversed.

The fact is that, if the problem wants to create a path from Henan to Gansu, it will need to locate some other paths to create a bigger path that connects those provinces. This job is handled in the objective function: its purpose is to minimize the amount of soldiers we encounter along the incursion, and since we need to fight the soldiers located in the province set as destination of our path (path[origin, destination]), the variable $x$ selects those paths which would allow us to fight the least amount of soldiers. Notice that those paths contained in model.paths (which are the paths between provinces with actual shared frontiers) are the only ones allowed to change their assigned value of $x$ to 1: using the previous example, the value of x["Henan", "Gansu"] will stay as a 0 (since it is not a pair located in model.paths), but x["Henan", "Shanxi"] = 1 and x["Shanxi", "Gansu"] = 1, so the final path would end linking this two provinces despite the fact that they have no shared frontier between them

In [15]:
model = ConcreteModel("Chinese Network Problem")

model.nodes = Set(initialize = provinces, doc = "Chinese provinces")
model.paths = Set(initialize = allborders, doc = "Links between provinces")
model.armies = Param(model.nodes, initialize = armies, doc = "Local armies at provinces")
model.prohibited_paths = Set(initialize = prohibited_paths, doc = "Prohibited paths to be traversed")


model.x = Var(model.nodes, model.nodes, domain = Binary, initialize = 0)
model.u = Var(model.nodes, domain = NonNegativeReals)

def objective_rule(model):
    return sum(model.x[o, d] * model.armies[d] for (o, d) in model.paths)
model.objective = Objective(rule = objective_rule, sense = minimize, doc = "Minimize enemies encountered")

$N$ = $\{1, 2, 3, \dots, 33\}$; $1 = Hebei, 2 = Shanxi, 3 = Liaoning, \dots, 33 = Hainan$; represents $model.nodes$

$P$ = $\{[1, 2], [1, 3], \dots, [33, 31], [33, 22]\}$; $[o, d] \in P$ if $o, d \in N$ and $o, d$ share border between them; represents $model.paths$

$A_p$ = Local army at the garrison in province $p$; represents $model.armies$

$K$ = $\{[18, 16], [24, 19], [14, 10]\}$; represents $model.prohibited\_paths$

$O$ = $\{29, 25, 23, 15\}$; represents the objectives to conquer

$x_{od}$ = Binary variable that checks if a certain path from province $o$ to province $d$ is used

$u_p$ = Positive discrete variable that assigns a value to a province $p$

$start$ = province at which the incursion starts

$end$ = province at which the incursion ends

The constraint initialization lasts, which will be in charge of selecting both the starting and ending point of the incursion and the mandatory provinces the US army has to traverse

The first one, the flow_constraint constraint is in charge of the proper management of the entrances and exits from each province. This means that the constraint is in charge of, firstly, keep a record on how many active paths (paths whose assigned value of $x$ is initialized as a 1, we will call them like this onwards for the sake of simplicity) have each province as origin and how many active paths have each province as destination, and checks that both are equal. If not, it makes sure that it is either a starting or an ending point, depending on the case

The following constraints are quite straightforward, these only define the mandatory provinces that are needed to be traversed. This is coded in the sense that the province mentioned in each of the constraints should be located in at least one fo the destinations of the active paths the model generates, or in other words, at least one active path has to have the province mentioned in each constraint as destination

Reaching the end there is the subtour_elimination_MTZ constraint. This constraint explains the existance of the other variable in the model, the variable u, since it is a mandatory variable needed to check the inexistance of any kind of cycle in our final pathing. The procedure shown here and the way it is coded is based on the Miller-Tucker-Zimler algorithm (more information about it on https://how-to.aimms.com/Articles/332/332-Miller-Tucker-Zemlin-formulation.html), but basically, it works by assigning some indexes to each node so that, if node $A$ is the origin of a path whose destination is node $B$, then the index of node $B$ has to be greater than node $A$, and no connection between a node with a greater index and a lower index can be made. This is how the creation of cycles is handled, and specially in this cases where some provinces must be traversed mandatory

And finally, it is necessary to create a constraint to check whether or not the paths prohibited to be traversed are, in fact, not traversed. This is achieved by checking if there is an active path between the origin and the destination of these prohibited paths and, if there is some of them, the constraint forces that active path to be removed (it would force the assigned $x$ to be a 0)

def flow_constraint(model, node):
    flowInNode = sum(model.x[o, d] for (o, d) in model.paths if d == node)
    flowOutNode = sum(model.x[o, d] for (o, d) in model.paths if o == node)
    if node == "Yunnan":
        return 1 + flowInNode == flowOutNode
    elif node == "Fujian":
        return flowInNode == flowOutNode + 1
    else:
        return flowInNode == flowOutNode
model.flow_constraint = Constraint(model.nodes, rule = flow_constraint, doc = "Manage flow throughout the network")

def objective_p1(model):
    return sum(model.x[o, d] for (o, d) in model.paths if d == "Beijing") >= 1
model.objective_p1 = Constraint(rule = objective_p1)

def objective_p2(model):
    return sum(model.x[o, d] for (o, d) in model.paths if d == "Shanghai") >= 1
model.objective_p2 = Constraint(rule = objective_p2)

def objective_p3(model):
    return sum(model.x[o, d] for (o, d) in model.paths if d == "Chongqing") >= 1
model.objective_p3 = Constraint(rule = objective_p3)

def objective_p4(model):
    return sum(model.x[o, d] for (o, d) in model.paths if d == "Guangdong") >= 1
model.objective_p4 = Constraint(rule = objective_p4)

# Template for additional objective provinces
# def objective_pX(model):
#     return sum(model.x[o, d] for (o, d) in model.paths if d == "X") >= 1
# model.objective_pX = Constraint(rule = objective_pX)

def subtour_elimination_MTZ(model, o, d):
    if o != d and (o, d) in model.paths:
        return model.u[o] - model.u[d] + len(model.nodes) * model.x[o, d] <= len(model.nodes) - 1
    return Constraint.Skip
model.subtour_elimination_constraint = Constraint(model.nodes, model.nodes, rule = subtour_elimination_MTZ) # USED MILLER TUCKER ZEMLIN https://how-to.aimms.com/Articles/332/332-Miller-Tucker-Zemlin-formulation.html

def path_prohibition(model, o, d):
    if [o, d] in model.prohibited_paths or [d, o] in model.prohibited_paths:
        return model.x[o, d] == 0
    return Constraint.Skip
model.path_prohibition_constraint = Constraint(model.nodes, model.nodes, rule = path_prohibition)

So, in the end, we end up with the following model:

Objective function & constraints:

$min. \sum_{o = 1}^{33}\sum_{d = 1}^{33}A_dx_{od}$

$s.t.$

$\sum_{o = 1}^{33}x_{op} = \sum_{d = 1}^{33}x_{pd}$, $\forall$ $p$ $in$ $N/${start, end}

$\sum_{o = 1}^{33}x_{os} + 1 = \sum_{d = 1}^{33}x_{sd}$, $s = start$

$\sum_{o = 1}^{33}x_{oe} = \sum_{d = 1}^{33}x_{ed} + 1$, $e = end$

$\sum_{o = 1}^{33}x_{od} \geq 1$, $\forall$ $d$ $in$ $O$ if $[o, d]$ $in$ $P$

$u_o - u_d + 33 * x_{od} \leq 32$, $\forall$ $[o, d]$ $in$ $P$ and $o$ $\neq$ $d$

$x_{od} = 0$, if $[o, d]$ $in$ $K$

From now on, it is just a matter of knowing which connections are made between the nodes by the detection of the different paths contained in the problem whose value has been initialized to 1 (in other words, which x is initialized as a 1). This will give us all the paths that, after being joint in a single path, will start and end at the desired nodes passing throught the provinces defined in the constraints

On the following table it is noticeable the different zeros and ones that comprend the whole list of paths, including the impossible ones like the one connecting provinces without a shared border or the ones linking a certain province with themselves. It is also noticeable how the mayority of them have the state Stale == True. This is explained as those paths that have that label were not used in any of the constraints, since we are only updating the values of those paths belonging to the lists in the list allborders. And in the end, notice that those paths that were prohibited to be traversed stay as zero, whether they were part of the optimal pathing without restrictions or not, and that

Second optimization practice. Network exercise: Football teams popularity¶

The FIFA has been wanting to make some use out of the money it has been given by the different clubs, and their best idea is to invest it into the creation of a ranking of the best supporters from all the different football teams in terms of healthiness: for example, a football team with supporters that start yelling when losing and fighting the police in the streets will have a lower popularity score than another one that politely accepts the results and do not start a fight with anyone on the streets. In order to do so, FIFA asked a certain company, Rankings S.A., about the creation of an algorithm that takes care about it, company to which gave some relevant information about the different clubs across the world

In this case, the company has tried to create an optimization ranking algorithm based on just five aspects of the teams statistics, which applied to the model they have created, these aspects are translated into five different variables:

1.: The amount of goals scored during the previous year. This variable will be defined in the model as $model.g$

2.: The budget or the the hypothetical price of the team. This variable will take the name of $model.b$ and it is measured in millions of dollars

3.: The amount of sponsors a team has. Will be called in the model as $model.s$

4.: The amount of trophies and championships won. This variable has the name of $model.t$ in the model

5.: The amount of corruption cases and controversial involvements. It is defined as $model.c$

In [19]:
# Imports
from pyomo.environ import *  
import random
import pandas as pd
In [20]:
model = ConcreteModel("Popularity of a team")

model.g = Var(domain = NonNegativeIntegers, initialize = 200, doc = "Goals scored last") 
model.b = Var(domain = NonNegativeReals, initialize = 400, doc = "Anual budget of the team")
model.s = Var(domain = NonNegativeIntegers, initialize = 30, doc = "Amount of sponsors")
model.t = Var(domain = NonNegativeIntegers, initialize = 50, doc = "Amount of trophies and cups")
model.c = Var(domain = NonNegativeIntegers, initialize = 40, doc = "Amount of corruption cases")

The previous variables will have to follow some kind of rule. For example, and the most straightforward rule, is that neither of these variables can be negative, and that the mayority of them have to be integers, since it is a non-sense that a team scored 68.5 goals last year or had -3 polemics along its history. But from now on, we will have to enter more in depth into the different constraints that the company Rankings S.A. has to define

So now, it is time to define mathematically the problem. In order to define the functions, we will define first the variables:

$G$ $\in$ $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$, represents $model.g$

$B$ = $\{50, \infty\}$, $B$ $\in$ $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$, represents $model.b$

$S$ = $\{0, 1, 2, \dots, 20\}$, represents $model.s$

$T$ $\in$ $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$, represents $model.t$

$C$ $\in$ $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$, represents $model.c$

And now, we should define some numerical constraints. Since the FIFA does not want to create a huge dataset of all the different teams across the world, but instead the most important ones, it has imposed that in the ranking only those teams that exceed the sale price of 50 million dollars. Apart from that FIFA also launched some new regulations that imposed a maximum amount of sponsors per team, which has to be capped at 20 sponsors

From now on, it has been a hard research of the statistics department of Rankings S.A., but they have ended up extracting some hidden relations between the different variables. For example, a relation between the commercial price of the company and the amount fo corruption cases was discovered, which is understandable since the more money a team moves, the more likely is to appear any kind of favourable treatments from the management team of the former team. Some more relations have been discovered, as for example, that sponsors raises a little bit the commercial price of the company, that the amount of trophies won is based on the amount of goals scored, which makes sense, or that the amount of goals a team scores is capped on the budget of the team. The latter relations makes special sense since those teams with more money can afford the best players with the best physical aptitudes, and then the best performance of the team would imply a higher amount of goals

def objective_rule(model):
    return 4 * model.g + 1.75 * model.b + (model.b * model.s / 200) + 6 * model.t - (model.c**3)
    #return (model.g + model.b + model.s + model.t - (model.c**2))
model.objective = Objective(expr = objective_rule, sense = maximize, doc = "Popularity of a team")

def min_budget(model):
    return model.b >= 50
model.min_budget_constraint = Constraint(expr = min_budget, doc = "Minimum budget")

def max_sponsors(model):
    return model.s <= 20
model.sponsors_20_constraint = Constraint(expr = max_sponsors, doc = "Maximum amount of sponsors")

def corruption_cases(model):
    #return model.c >= 1.75*log(model.b)
    return model.c >= 3**(model.b/2000)
    # Add more functions
model.corruption_cases_constraint = Constraint(expr = corruption_cases, doc = "Corruption functions")

def goals_scored(model):
    return model.g <= 40 * log10(model.b)
model.goals_scored_constraint = Constraint(expr = goals_scored, doc = "Goals scored")

def trophies_won(model):
    return model.t <= model.g / 25
model.trophies_won_constraint = Constraint(expr = trophies_won, doc = "Trophies won")

So in the end, we end up with the following model:

Objective function & constraints:

$max.$ $4G$ + $1.75B$ + $(\frac{BS}{200})$ + $6T$ - $C^3$

$s.t.$

$B$ $\geq$ $50$

$S$ $\leq$ $20$

$C$ $\geq$ $3^{\frac{B}{2000}}$

$G$ $\leq$ $40\log_{10}{B}$

$T$ $\leq$ $\frac{G}{25}$

From now on, we can end up solving this problem. But beforehand, we can extract some hypothesis from the model. The first one is that since the only variable that actually lowers the popularity score of a team is the amount of corruption cases, we would like it to be the smallest as possible, but since it is directly influenced by the budget, which is also the main variable used to increase the amount of goals scored, tropies and sponsors, then the final results should be somewhere in a middle point in where the budget is not that high so that corruption cases start increasing in a dangerous manner but not that little where the team has a small upperbound of goals, which entails a low amount of trophies and thus, a small group of supporters with a low popularity ranking

    return 4 * g + 1.75 * b + (b * s / 200) + 6 * t - (c**3)

And in fact, we end up with the previous values to be the best variables for the ranking problem. This means that any team that gets near these values should have it easy to be on one of the top spots of the ranking. In order to get them, the solver ipopt has managed to shown us some parameters of the process followed in a kind of report. On it, we are shown some values, like the amount of variables with lower and upper bounds, which are 5 and 4 respectively: not only the numerical constraints are taken into account here, like the max_sponsors, but also those constraints affecting some more variables, like the constraint corruption_cases. Notice that these results have been achieved through a certain amount of iterations, which in this case they were 20 iterations. Notice also that the non linear error provided by this algorithm is in the order of $2.5^{-9}$, which is a quite good error to have in this kind of exercises, specially when we are working with values that are at least 9 orders of magnitude over the error provided

If you notice, since ipopt is a continuous solver, the output would also end up being continuous, which ended up with decimals in the variables despite the fact that those were defined as non negative integers on the initialization. As we can see, the hypothesis we were discussing right before the solver execution was right, the budget is not that low so that no trophies are achieved but not that high so that corruption cases do not go out of hand and decreases the team reputation that much
